07702nam a22019095i 9780691242682DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912426827 a10.1515/97806912426822doi  a(DE-B1597)644685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB815b.A44 2023 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a128/.37223/eng/202302111 aAlessandri, Mariana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNight Vision :bSeeing Ourselves through Dark Moods /cMariana Alessandri. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Doubting the Light -- t1. Getting Honest about Anger -- t2. I Suffer, Therefore I Am -- t3. Grieving Stubbornly -- t4. Recoloring Depression -- t5. Learning to Be Anxious -- tConclusion: Practicing Night Vision -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA philosopher’s personal meditation on how painful emotions can reveal truths about what it means to be truly humanUnder the light of ancient Western philosophies, our darker moods like grief, anguish, and depression can seem irrational. When viewed through the lens of modern psychology, they can even look like mental disorders. The self-help industry, determined to sell us the promise of a brighter future, can sometimes leave us feeling ashamed that we are not more grateful, happy, or optimistic. Night Vision invites us to consider a different approach to life, one in which we stop feeling bad about feeling bad.In this powerful and disarmingly intimate book, Existentialist philosopher Mariana Alessandri draws on the stories of a diverse group of nineteenth- and twentieth-century philosophers and writers to help us see that our suffering is a sign not that we are broken but that we are tender, perceptive, and intelligent. Thinkers such as Audre Lorde, María Lugones, Miguel de Unamuno, C. S. Lewis, Gloria Anzaldúa, and Søren Kierkegaard sat in their anger, sadness, and anxiety until their eyes adjusted to the dark. Alessandri explains how readers can cultivate “night vision” and discover new sides to their painful moods, such as wit and humor, closeness and warmth, and connection and clarity.Night Vision shows how, when we learn to embrace the dark, we begin to see these moods—and ourselves—as honorable, dignified, and unmistakably human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEmotions (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAdult.  aAmerican poetry.  aAndrew Solomon.  aAnger.  aAngry mob.  aAnxiety.  aAsher Brown Durand.  aAttention span.  aAudre Lorde.  aBehavior.  aBipolar disorder.  aBlack people.  aBlank verse.  aBullying.  aCapitol police.  aClergy.  aCoatlicue.  aCognitive behavioral therapy.  aComfort.  aCondolences.  aConsumerism.  aCoronavirus.  aCovid-19.  aCredibility.  aCrying.  aDuke University Press.  aEmil Kraepelin.  aEmoticon.  aEpicurus.  aEthos.  aExaltation (astrology).  aExistentialism.  aFeeling.  aFireplace.  aGood and evil.  aGood cop/bad cop.  aGrief.  aHatred.  aHoward Thurman.  aHuitzilopochtli.  aHypoglycemia.  aImbecile.  aImpostor syndrome.  aIncest.  aIrony.  aIrritation.  aLaw of attraction (New Thought).  aLaziness.  aLearning.  aMental disorder.  aMental health professional.  aMexican Americans.  aMood (psychology).  aMotivation.  aMourning and Melancholia.  aNational Women's Rights Convention.  aNeurasthenia.  aOf Modern Poetry.  aPain.  aParenting.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPity.  aPleasure.  aP